<doc id="1137612" wikidata="Q970767" url="?curid=1137612" title="Generalized eigenvector">
<text>In linear algebra, a generalized eigenvector of an formula_1 matrix formula_2 is a vector which satisfies certain criteria which are more relaxed than those for an (ordinary) eigenvector.

Let formula_3 be an formula_4-dimensional vector space and let formula_2 be the matrix representation of a linear map from formula_3 to formula_3 with respect to some ordered basis.

There may not always exist a full set of formula_4 linearly independent eigenvectors of formula_2 that form a complete basis for formula_3. That is, the matrix formula_2 may not be diagonalizable. This happens when the algebraic multiplicity of at least one eigenvalue formula_12 is greater than its geometric multiplicity (the nullity of the matrix formula_13, or the dimension of its nullspace). In this case, formula_12 is called a defective eigenvalue and formula_2 is called a defective matrix.

A generalized eigenvector formula_16 corresponding to formula_12, together with the matrix formula_13 generate a Jordan chain of linearly independent generalized eigenvectors which form a basis for an invariant subspace of formula_3.

Using generalized eigenvectors, a set of linearly independent eigenvectors of formula_2 can be extended, if necessary, to a complete basis for formula_3. This basis can be used to determine an &quot;almost diagonal matrix&quot; formula_22 in Jordan normal form, similar to formula_2, which is useful in computing certain matrix functions of formula_2. The matrix formula_22 is also useful in solving the system of linear differential equations formula_26 where formula_2 need not be diagonalizable.

The dimension of the generalized eigenspace corresponding to a given eigenvalue formula_28 is the algebraic multiplicity of formula_28.

== Overview and definition ==
There are several equivalent ways to define an ordinary eigenvector. For our purposes, an eigenvector formula_30 associated with an eigenvalue formula_28 of an formula_4 × formula_4 matrix formula_2 is a nonzero vector for which formula_35, where formula_36 is the formula_4 × formula_4 identity matrix and formula_39 is the zero vector of length formula_4. That is, formula_30 is in the kernel of the transformation formula_42. If formula_2 has formula_4 linearly independent eigenvectors, then formula_2 is similar to a diagonal matrix formula_46. That is, there exists an invertible matrix formula_47 such that formula_2 is diagonalizable through the similarity transformation formula_49. The matrix formula_46 is called a spectral matrix for formula_2. The matrix formula_47 is called a modal matrix for formula_2. Diagonalizable matrices are of particular interest since matrix functions of them can be computed easily.

On the other hand, if formula_2 does not have formula_4 linearly independent eigenvectors associated with it, then formula_2 is not diagonalizable.

Definition: A vector formula_57 is a generalized eigenvector of rank &quot;m&quot; of the matrix formula_2 and corresponding to the eigenvalue formula_28 if

:formula_60

but

:formula_61 

Clearly, a generalized eigenvector of rank 1 is an ordinary eigenvector. Every formula_4 × formula_4 matrix formula_2 has formula_4 linearly independent generalized eigenvectors associated with it and can be shown to be similar to an &quot;almost diagonal&quot; matrix formula_22 in Jordan normal form. That is, there exists an invertible matrix formula_47 such that formula_68. The matrix formula_47 in this case is called a generalized modal matrix for formula_2. If formula_28 is an eigenvalue of algebraic multiplicity formula_72, then formula_2 will have formula_72 linearly independent generalized eigenvectors corresponding to formula_28. These results, in turn, provide a straightforward method for computing certain matrix functions of formula_2.

Note: For an formula_77 matrix formula_2 over a field formula_79 to be expressed in Jordan normal form, all eigenvalues of formula_2 must be in formula_79. That is, the characteristic polynomial formula_82 must factor completely into linear factors; formula_79 must be an algebraically closed field. For example, if formula_2 has real-valued elements, then it may be necessary for the eigenvalues and the components of the eigenvectors to have complex values.

The set spanned by all generalized eigenvectors for a given formula_85 forms the generalized eigenspace for formula_85.

